describes \u003Cstrong\u003Eprophase\u003C/strong\u003E, the first phase of mitosis. During prophase, chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes, the nuclear envelope begins to break down, and the nucleolus disappears. These changes prepare the cell for chromosome segregation in the later phases of mitosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other phases have distinct characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterphase\u003C/strong\u003E is not technically a phase of mitosis - it is the period between divisions where DNA replication occurs and chromosomes remain as diffuse chromatin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetaphase\u003C/strong\u003E follows prophase and is characterised by chromosome alignment at the cell\u0027s equator (metaphase plate)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETelophase\u003C/strong\u003E is the final phase where the nuclear envelope reforms, chromosomes decondense, and the nucleolus reappears\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphase\u003C/strong\u003E involves the separation of sister chromatids as they are pulled towards opposite poles of the cell by spindle fibres\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe events of prophase are essential for preparing the chromosomes for proper segregation during cell division.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prophase is characterised by chromosome condensation and nuclear envelope breakdown","Chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes during prophase","The nuclear envelope disintegrates and nucleolus disappears during late prophase"],"references":["Alberts B, Bray D, Johnson A, Lewis J, Raff M, Roberts K, et al. Cell communities: tissues, stem cells, and cancer. Essential cell biology, 4th New York Edition: Garland Science; 2018.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019."